Thus, in covert ternis, he advises him to return to his merchandise, and trouble his head no more about philosophy. Wieland supposes that Horace, about this time, was improving the appearance of his Sabine farm, which he had received as a gist from his patron, and converting the small fami-house that stood on it into a kind of villa. This excited the ill-will of his enemies at Rome, and, as Maecenas at this same time was erecting his splendid residence on the Esquiline, they charged the poet with an attempt to ape the conduct of his superiors. It is to this that Horace pleasantly alludes, under the character of Damasippus.—Lon90s. “The great.’' There is a pun in this word, as opposed to moduli bipedalis, since it means tall as well as yreat.
